which _common_params() puts directly in the query string on every call,
would appear in cleartext in that exception's str(). This became the
headline finding; redirected focus from "is the retry logic complete" to
"is there an actual secrets-leak path," which the task brief explicitly
asked about (item 5).

[2026-07-04T16:05:00] TASK 1B REVIEW — COMPLETE

Findings (most severe first):

1. SIGNIFICANT — verified secret leak into logs via uncaught
   httpx.HTTPStatusError on non-429/non-5xx 4xx responses
   (backend/app/integrations/pubmed.py:262-276). _get() only special-cases
   429 and >=500; any other 4xx (e.g. NCBI 400 for a malformed query, or
   403 for a revoked api_key) falls through to response.raise_for_status()
   at line 275, which is outside the try/except httpx.HTTPError block
   (lines 234-244) — so the resulting httpx.HTTPStatusError propagates
   uncaught, contradicting the module's own documented contract that
   route handlers only need to catch PubMedUnavailableError. Verified via
   a local repro that httpx.HTTPStatusError's str() embeds the full
   request URL with query params in cleartext, e.g.:
   "Client error '403 Forbidden' for url '.../esearch.fcgi?email=secret%40example.com&api_key=SEKRET123'"
   Since _common_params() puts NCBI_EMAIL (real operator PII) and
   NCBI_API_KEY into every request's query string, any downstream log of
   str(exc) on this uncaught exception — which CONTRACTS.md line 203's
   "internal_error (500)... exception-shape guarantee" implies Task 3D's
   catch-all handler will eventually do before sanitizing the client
   response — leaks both into shared logs. No test in
   test_pubmed_client.py exercises any 4xx other than 429, so this gap
   was never caught by either the specialist or tester. tester's VERDICT
   ("MET") is accurate for everything it tested but doesn't flag this
   untested branch; not a false verdict, but an incomplete one.

2. MINOR — xml.etree.ElementTree (backend/app/integrations/pubmed.py:410)
   is not hardened against internal entity-expansion DoS (billion
   laughs/quadratic blowup), though confirmed NOT vulnerable to XXE
   (external entity resolution is not enabled by default in stdlib
   ElementTree). Low realistic exploitability since the XML always comes
   from a fixed HTTPS-pinned host (eutils.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov), not arbitrary
   user input, but defusedxml would close this cheaply.

3. Verified correct, not a finding — outbound RateLimiter concurrency.
   Independently ran RateLimiter(10.0) against 6 truly concurrent
   coroutines via asyncio.gather (existing test suite only exercises
   sequential awaits) and confirmed the asyncio.Lock-guarded
   check-and-update correctly holds ~0.1s spacing every time — no
   TOCTOU race for concurrent callers. Existing tests don't actually prove
   this (only sequential pacing is tested), so this correctness had to be
   verified out-of-band rather than taken on the log's word.

4. Verified correct, not a finding — iCite degradation (§7.6). All three
   failure classes (ConnectError, 5xx, malformed JSON) collapse to
   available=False, and that's spec-correct here since iCite has no
   auth/config that could produce a distinguishable "persistent
   misconfiguration" state worth surfacing separately.

5. Verified correct, not a finding — zero-result/partial-batch malformed-
   record handling (§7.9). Traced (not just trusted test names) the
   per-uid skip in esummary() and the per-PubmedArticle try/except in
   _parse_efetch_xml — one bad record doesn't fail the batch. An empty-
   but-present <Abstract> element also degrades cleanly (untested
   explicitly but structurally safe).

Overall: 1 significant, 1 minor. Not a clean pass — the significant
finding is a real, reproduced secrets-leak path, not a theoretical
concern, and both the specialist's and tester's logs missed it because no
test exercises a non-429/5xx 4xx response. Reported to orchestrator for
routing back to senior-backend-developer (fix: wrap raise_for_status()
inside the same try/except and convert to PubMedUnavailableError with a
scrubbed message, or catch httpx.HTTPStatusError explicitly) and to
tester (add a 400/403 fixture case to close the coverage gap).

