Findings, most severe first:

1. SIGNIFICANT — normalize.py's statistical-notation expansion has no
   handling for ≤/≥ (only ASCII <, >, =), so p-value thresholds written
   with these very common Unicode comparison operators pass through
   completely unexpanded. Confirmed live:
   `normalize_for_speech("p ≤ 0.05 was considered significant.")` returns
   the string unchanged — the ≤ symbol is never converted to "less than
   or equal to" the way §6.3's own worked example does for plain "<".
   This isn't a hypothetical: ≤/≥ p-value notation ("p ≤ 0.001") is at
   least as common in PubMed abstracts as the plain "<" SPEC.md's worked
   example uses, and a TTS engine that silently skips an unrecognized
   Unicode comparison glyph (the exact failure mode §6.3 explicitly
   warns about for Greek letters — "rather than being skipped or read as
   'unknown character' silence") would narrate "p 0.05" with the
   comparison direction lost entirely, changing what the listener
   believes was reported. Not cited by SPEC.md's literal worked examples
   (only <, =, ±, % are enumerated), so this is a coverage gap within
   1D's own declared scope rather than a contradiction of an explicit
   spec line — but it's squarely inside the "Statistical & mathematical
   notation" bullet's stated intent. test_normalize.py has zero cases
   for ≤/≥ (grep confirms). Recommend fixing in 1D now (same three-line
   pattern as the existing </>/= handling) rather than letting it ship;
   cheap, and it's exactly the class of thing that's expensive to
   retrofit once outbound narration behavior is depended on by 2D's
   playback engine.

2. MINOR — the same math-operator regexes (`<\s*(number)`, `>\s*(number)`,
   `=\s*(number)`) don't accept a leading minus sign, so negative
   statistical values silently drop the operator word instead of just
   the number: confirmed `normalize_for_speech("r = -0.34, p < 0.001.")`
   → `"r = -0.34, p less than 0.001."` — the "=" before -0.34 is left as
   a literal unspoken symbol while "p < 0.001" correctly expands to
   "less than" right next to it in the same sentence, an inconsistency
   a listener would notice. Not meaning-changing (the negative number
   itself survives intact, just missing "equals"), so minor rather than
   significant, but worth a follow-up ticket alongside finding 1 since
   both are in the same operator-regex code path already being touched.

3. Tester's two integration-gap findings (7a: duplicate `AbstractSection`
   dataclass between pubmed.py line 147 and tokenize.py line 251; 7b: no
   flattened spoken-text equivalent returned by `build_segmented_
   abstract()` despite CONTRACTS.md §1 saying `spoken_text` is "sourced
   from `Paper.spoken_abstract`") — both independently confirmed real:
   - 7a confirmed via direct read of both files: identical fields
     (`label: str | None`, `text: str`), two separate frozen dataclasses,
     no shared import between pubmed.py and tokenize.py. Checked whether
     unifying them would break either test suite: `test_pubmed.py`
     doesn't exist as such but grep of test_tokenize.py shows only
     keyword-arg construction (`AbstractSection(label=..., text=...)`),
     no isinstance/type-identity assertions — a straight import swap in
     either direction is a safe, low-risk, single-line-per-file fix.
     Recommend FIX NOW, not defer to 3A: both files are fresh/uncommitted
     in this same wave, the fix is trivial, and deferring risks the two
     copies silently diverging later (e.g. if 1B ever adds a field to
     support §7.5 more fully) which would turn a one-line import fix
     into a real refactor. This is also a direct instance of the
     project's own stated single-source-of-truth discipline (the same
     principle 1D's own docstring invokes for segmentation logic)
     applied to the data shape, not just the logic.
   - 7b confirmed via grep (`spoken_abstract` appears only in
     entities.py, nowhere else in backend/app/) and by reading
     `build_segmented_abstract()` end-to-end: it returns only
     `(display_abstract, SegmentedAbstractResponse)`, with `spoken_text`
     computed per-segment but never joined into a flattened string
     analogous to `display_parts`/`display_abstract`. Recommend FIX NOW
     as well: the fix is a parallel accumulator to the existing
     `display_parts` list (a `spoken_parts` list appending each
     segment's `spoken_text`, joined the same way) — a few-line change
     to a function 1D already owns and has fully tested, versus asking
     Task 3A to reconstruct the exact same section/sentence-join
     convention (which section separator, whether headers are included,
     trailing-space handling) from scratch, which is exactly the kind of
     "re-derive a decision that should live in one place" risk
     BuildPlan.md's single-source-of-truth note for this module warns
     against. Neither gap blocks Task 1D's own merge (its cited tests
     are genuinely green and correct in isolation), but both are cheap
     enough right now that carrying them forward as "Task 3A backlog"
